                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d211">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Clayton</persName>, Secretary of
                        State, to Mr. <persName type="to">Hall</persName>, district attorney.</hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1849-09-19">
                        <hi rend="italic">September</hi> 19, 1849</date>.</dateline>
                <p>
                    <seg type="margin">[657]</seg> *<hi rend="smallcaps">J. Prescott Hall</hi>, Esq.,<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">United States District Attorney for the Southern District of
                        New York</hi>.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In acknowledging the receipt of your letter of
                    the 15th instant, it is due to you to say, that the President highly approves of
                    the prompt, energetic, and judicious manner in which you have executed all the
                    instructions of this Department, touching the late attempt on the part of some
                    of our misguided citizens, who were concerned in a mischievous and illegal
                    project for the invasion of the island of Cuba. To this expression from the
                    President I have great pleasure in adding this Department’s unqualified
                    approbation of your official conduct.</p>
                <p>I am, sir, with great respect, your obedient servant,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>JOHN M. CLAYTON.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
